Hacking LLMs: A Technical Analysis of Security
Vulnerabilities and Defense Mechanisms
Gaurav Raj Sharda University gaurav.raj@sharda.ac.in
Hamzah Sharda University 2022395985.hamzah@ug.sharda.ac.in
Nikhil Raj Sharda University 2022515845.nikhil@ug.sharda.ac.in
Abstract—Large Language Models (LLMs) such as GPT-4 and Google’s Gemini have revolutionized the landscape of artificial intelligence, enabling sophisticated natural language processing capabilities across diverse domains. However, the rapid adoption of these models has unveiled a spectrum of security vulnerabilities exploitable by adversaries [1], [2]. This paper presents a comprehensive analysis of various attack vectors targeting LLMs, including prompt injection, data poisoning, model inversion, and side-channel attacks. We examine real-world incidents and vulnerabilities discovered in widely-used LLMs like ChatGPT and Gemini [3], highlighting the intricate mechanisms through which these attacks compromise model integrity and user trust. Furthermore, we explore existing defense mechanisms and best practices, emphasizing runtime protection systems, adversarial training approaches, and robust access control systems [4], [5]. Building upon these foundations, we introduce a novel MultiLayer Defense Framework with Dynamic Trust Scoring, designed to enhance the security and robustness of LLM deployments through dynamic evaluation and adaptive response systems. By dissecting recent advancements in LLM security research and proposing innovative defense strategies, this paper aims to guide the development of resilient defenses against the evolving landscape of AI-driven threats. Index Terms—Large Language Models, LLM Security, Prompt Injection, Data Poisoning, Model Inversion, Side-Channel Attacks, Adversarial Training, Runtime Protection, Multi-Layer Defense Framework, Dynamic Trust Scoring
I. INTRODUCTION
A. Background on Large Language Models (LLMs)
[1]. However, as with any powerful technology, the broader adoption of LLMs brings forth significant security challenges. The very features that make LLMs versatile—such as their capacity for prompt adaptation and contextual reasoning—also expose them to novel attack vectors that were previously unseen in traditional software [9].
B. Importance of Security in LLMs
LLMs are critical in domains such as healthcare, law, and finance, where security breaches can lead to data leaks, misinformation, and compromised decision-making [10,11]. For example, vulnerabilities in Google’s Gemini enabled prompt injections that exposed sensitive information [1,12]. These incidents underscore the urgent need for robust security protocols in LLM deployments.
C. Overview of LLM Vulnerabilities
LLMs face several key vulnerabilities that can compromise system integrity: • Input Manipulation: Including prompt injection, data poisoning, and adversarial attacks that force erroneous behavior. • Data Extraction: Through model inversion and extraction attacks that reveal sensitive information.
• Insecure Output Handling: Insufficient validation may lead to system breaches. These challenges necessitate robust, multi-layered defense strategies.
II. ATTACKS ON LLMS: TYPES AND TECHNIQUES
A. Data Poisoning Attacks
1) Description and Methodology: Data poisoning attacks involve injecting malicious data into the training dataset of an LLM to alter its behavior in a way that benefits the attacker [18]. Given the vast amounts of data LLMs consume, even a small percentage of poisoned data can have a significant impact.
Mechanism of Data Poisoning:
• Injection of Malicious Data: Attackers introduce false or misleading data into the training set [18] • Manipulation of Labels: Incorrect labeling of data points to confuse the model [19] • Backdoor Triggers: Embedding specific patterns that activate malicious behavior when encountered [6]
