B. Adversarial Examples
1) Crafting Adversarial Inputs: Adversarial examples are inputs crafted to cause an LLM to make mistakes or produce unintended outputs [9]. These inputs often contain minimal perturbations that are imperceptible to humans but significantly impact the model’s performance [10].
Techniques for Generating Adversarial Inputs: • Synonym Replacement [11]: – Replace words with their synonyms to alter the model’s prediction – Example: ∗ Original: ”The movie was good.” ∗ Adversarial: ”The movie was adequate.” • Gradient-Based Methods [12]: – Use gradients to identify which input changes maximize the loss function
2) Case Studies: Case Study 1: TextFooler Attack
TextFooler is an adversarial attack algorithm that modifies text inputs to fool NLP models without changing human perception [13], [14]. Process:
• Identify important words influencing the model’s decision [15] • Replace them with synonyms or similar words [16] • Ensure grammatical correctness and semantic similarity [17]
