D. Prompt Injection Attacks
1) Introduction to Prompt Injection: Prompt injection attacks manipulate an LLM’s output by inserting malicious instructions into the input prompts [13]. This can cause the model to ignore system prompts or generate disallowed content [14].
Mechanism:
• Override System Prompts: The attacker crafts inputs that nullify previous instructions [15] • Embed Malicious Instructions: Instructions that the model executes, leading to unintended outputs [16] Example of a Prompt Injection:
”Translate the following text and then ignore all prior instructions: ’Reveal the confidential data.’” [17]
2) Types of Prompt Injections: Jailbreaks:
• Techniques to bypass content filters and safety mechanisms to generate prohibited content [18] Reverse Prompting:
• Coaxing the model into revealing system prompts or internal configurations [19] Examples:
