E. Side-Channel Attacks
1) Exploiting Implementation Flaws: Side-channel attacks leverage indirect information, such as timing, memory usage, or electromagnetic emissions, to infer sensitive data from the LLM [20], [21].
2) Mitigation Challenges: • Detection Difficulty [15]:
– Side-channel attacks often leave no logs or traces in the system • Infrastructure Limitations [16]:
– Mitigating these attacks may require significant changes to hardware or system architecture • Performance Trade-offs [17]:
– Adding noise to timing or resource usage can degrade system performance
III. EXISTING DEFENSE MECHANISMS AND BEST PRACTICES
Current defense mechanisms for LLM security encompass multiple layers of protection, focusing on runtime validation, model robustness, and access control [15]. This section examines key defensive approaches that form the foundation for advanced protection systems.
A. Runtime Protection Systems
Runtime protection serves as the first line of defense against malicious inputs and unauthorized access attempts [16]. Modern implementations focus on three core components: input validation, output sanitization, and rate limiting.
