D. Adaptive Response System
The Adaptive Response System dynamically adjusts the system’s behavior based on the outcomes of the validation layers, ensuring appropriate mitigation of detected threats. 1) Response Throttling: Implements mechanisms to control the rate and volume of responses based on the assessed trust level of incoming queries. a) Dynamic Rate Limiting: Adjusts the rate limits in realtime according to the trust scores, preventing potential abuse while allowing legitimate usage.
b) Progressive Restrictions: Applies escalating restrictions for repeated or severe violations, such as temporarily blocking a user after multiple failed validations. 2) Alert Generation: Facilitates the prompt notification of administrators upon detection of potential threats, enabling swift response actions.
a) Threat Level Classification: Categorizes detected threats based on their severity and potential impact, ensuring that high-priority alerts receive immediate attention.
b) Administrator Notifications: Sends notifications to system administrators through various channels (e.g., email, dashboards) to inform them of detected threats and necessary actions.
V. IMPLEMENTATION AND EVALUATION
The proposed Multi-Layer Defense Framework was implemented on a standard multi-core CPU system (16GB RAM, SSD storage) and evaluated using synthetic and real-world datasets. Evaluation Metrics: Detection accuracy (96%), false positive rate (¡1.8%), processing overhead ( 7%), and response time confirmed real-time applicability. Implementation Details: Key components (Trust Scoring Engine and Adaptive Response Module) were developed in Python using TensorFlow/PyTorch. Queries were processed through cascading validation layers, with an API Gateway and middleware ensuring seamless integration.
Real-World Simulation: Attack scenarios—including prompt injection, data poisoning, and adversarial examples—were simulated using public and proprietary datasets. The framework thwarted 98% of attacks. Discussion: These results demonstrate that our framework effectively enhances security while preserving system perfor
mance. VI. CONCLUSION
This paper examined the vulnerabilities of LLMs—including prompt injection, data poisoning, model inversion, and side-channel attacks—and reviewed defense strategies such as runtime protection, adversarial training, and access control. We proposed a Multi-Layer Defense Framework with Dynamic Trust Scoring that achieved high detection accuracy, low false positives, and effective attack prevention in simulated tests. Future work will optimize the machine learning components, enhance scalability, and establish standardized security protocols.
